## Phase 0.5: Research method selection

Before drafting the test plan, identify the right research method. The right method depends on where the initiative sits in the Double Diamond: are you still exploring the problem (Discover) or evaluating a solution (Deliver)?

**Read the upstream context** to determine the phase:
- If the initiative has no prototype or design yet → problem space (Discover)
- If a concept or design exists and needs evaluation → solution space (Deliver)

**Discover (problem space) methods:**
- **Generative interviews** — understand why users behave as they do. n≥8. Best when: the root cause is unknown, hypotheses need grounding in real user experience before any design starts.
- **Diary study** — understand behaviour over time. n≥10. Best when: the behaviour is episodic or hard to recall accurately in a single session.

**Deliver (solution space) methods:**
- **Concept test** — does the concept effectively solve the problem? n≥7. Best when: testing whether users understand and value the solution direction before any engineering commitment.
- **Usability test** — can users accomplish key tasks? n≥5. Best when: a design exists and you need to identify friction, confusion, and failure points in the flow. Nielsen: 5 users often uncover ~80% of usability issues. Increase n if testing multiple segments or running unmoderated.

Use AskUserQuestion to present the options. Format your question as:

```
Re-ground: [initiative name], [Discover or Deliver phase], choosing research method before designing the test plan.
Simplify: The method we choose shapes everything — the tasks, the questions, the participant count, and what we can conclude. Picking the wrong method wastes time and produces misleading signal.
RECOMMENDATION: [Method] because [one-line rationale derived from the upstream artifacts].
A) [Option 1] — n=[sample size]. [One-line rationale.]
B) [Option 2] — n=[sample size]. [One-line rationale.]
C) [Option 3 if applicable] — n=[sample size]. [One-line rationale.]
```

Carry the confirmed method and n= into Phase 1 — they determine the participant count, task structure, and success thresholds in the test plan.

